As of my writing this (April 2nd), the death toll in Spain due to coronavirus is 10,348. Spain's first death occurred on March 3rd, 30 days ago. If we extrapolate an exponential function from this to find the death rate and predict death counts for future days, using f(x) = a(b)^x, we get 10,348 = 1(b)^30, which simplifies to a death rate of the 30th root of 10,348, which is 36%. If we are optimistic and assume that Spain's lockdown will cut transmission and thus death rates by 50%, giving us a death rate of 18% going forward, and want to find the number of deaths on May 1st, which is 31 days from now, we can use the expression 10,348(1.18)^31 to come to a total number of 1,750,647 deaths. Of course there are many other factors that will lower the death count such as the building of new hospitals, increased efficiency of social distancing among the population, an increased medical supply, etc, one can be 100% confident any measures could be enacted this late in the timeline to reduce that death count below 15,000. https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/spain/.

Referencing Italy's CFR, which was 7.9% on 2020 Mar 18th, as Spain is on 2020 Mar 29th. Italy's CFR is now >10%, 11 days later. Suppose Spain follows same trajectory, and reach CFR 10% and stays there till May 1st. From another question, I forecasted Spain would have 95% chance of having >180K confirmed cases by May 1st. 10% of this is 18K. Hence forecasting 95% chance Spain will have >15K deaths by May 1st.
